# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sparse-linear-algebra
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] In mathematics, particularly matrix theory, a **band matrix** or **banded matrix** is a sparse matrix whose non-zero entries are confined to a diagonal *band*, comprising the main diagonal and zero or more diagonals on either side.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] then the quantities *k*1 and *k*2 are called the **lower bandwidth** and **upper bandwidth**, respectively.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] The **bandwidth** of the matrix is the maximum of *k*1 and *k*2; in other words, it is the number *k* such that $a_{i,j}=0$ if $|i-j|>k$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] In numerical analysis, matrices from finite element or finite difference problems are often banded.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] Such matrices can be viewed as descriptions of the coupling between the problem variables; the banded property corresponds to the fact that variables are not coupled over arbitrarily large distances.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] Such matrices can be further divided – for instance, banded matrices exist where every element in the band is nonzero.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] Problems in higher dimensions also lead to banded matrices, in which case the band itself also tends to be sparse.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] For instance, a partial differential equation on a square domain (using central differences) will yield a matrix with a bandwidth equal to the square root of the matrix dimension, but inside the band only 5 diagonals are nonzero.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] Unfortunately, applying Gaussian elimination (or equivalently an LU decomposition) to such a matrix results in the band being filled in by many non-zero elements.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] Band matrices are usually stored by storing the diagonals in the band; the rest is implicitly zero.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] For example, a tridiagonal matrix has bandwidth 1.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] A further saving is possible when the matrix is symmetric.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] From a computational point of view, working with band matrices is always preferential to working with similarly dimensioned square matrices.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] A band matrix can be likened in complexity to a rectangular matrix whose row dimension is equal to the bandwidth of the band matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] Thus the work involved in performing operations such as multiplication falls significantly, often leading to huge savings in terms of calculation time and complexity.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] The Cuthill–McKee algorithm can be used to reduce the bandwidth of a sparse symmetric matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] There are, however, matrices for which the reverse Cuthill–McKee algorithm performs better.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/band-matrix] The problem of finding a representation of a matrix with minimal bandwidth by means of permutations of rows and columns is NP-hard.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In mathematics, the **conjugate gradient method** is an algorithm for the numerical solution of particular systems of linear equations, namely those whose matrix is positive-semidefinite.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method is often implemented as an iterative algorithm, applicable to sparse systems that are too large to be handled by a direct implementation or other direct methods such as the Cholesky decomposition.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Large sparse systems often arise when numerically solving partial differential equations or optimization problems.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can also be used to solve unconstrained optimization problems such as energy minimization.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] It is commonly attributed to Magnus Hestenes and Eduard Stiefel, who programmed it on the Z4, and extensively researched it.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The biconjugate gradient method provides a generalization to non-symmetric matrices.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Various nonlinear conjugate gradient methods seek minima of nonlinear optimization problems.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] We denote the unique solution of this system by $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can be derived from several different perspectives, including specialization of the conjugate direction method for optimization, and variation of the Arnoldi/Lanczos iteration for eigenvalue problems.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Despite differences in their approaches, these derivations share a common topic—proving the orthogonality of the residuals and conjugacy of the search directions.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] These two properties are crucial to developing the well-known succinct formulation of the method.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Two vectors are conjugate if and only if they are orthogonal with respect to this inner product.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Being conjugate is a symmetric relation: if $\mathbf {u}$ is conjugate to $\mathbf {v}$ , then $\mathbf {v}$ is conjugate to $\mathbf {u}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] is a set of n mutually conjugate vectors with respect to $\mathbf {A}$ , i.e. $\mathbf {p} _{i}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {A} \mathbf {p} _{j}=0$ for all $i\neq j$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This gives the following method for solving the equation $\mathbf {Ax} =\mathbf {b}$ : find a sequence of n conjugate directions, and then compute the coefficients $\alpha _{k}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] If we choose the conjugate vectors $\mathbf {p} _{k}$ carefully, then we may not need all of them to obtain a good approximation to the solution $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] So, we want to regard the conjugate gradient method as an iterative method.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This also allows us to approximately solve systems where n is so large that the direct method would take too much time.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] We denote the initial guess for $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ by $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ (we can assume without loss of generality that $\mathbf {x} _{0}=\mathbf {0}$ , otherwise consider the system $\mathbf {Az} =\mathbf {b} -\mathbf {Ax} _{0}$ instead).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Starting with $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ we search for the solution and in each iteration we need a metric to tell us whether we are closer to the solution $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ (that is unknown to us).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This suggests taking the first basis vector $\mathbf {p} _{0}$ to be the negative of the gradient of f at $\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {x} _{0}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The gradient of f equals $\mathbf {Ax} -\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Starting with an initial guess $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ , this means we take $\mathbf {p} _{0}=\mathbf {b} -\mathbf {Ax} _{0}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The other vectors in the basis will be conjugate to the gradient, hence the name *conjugate gradient method*.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Note that $\mathbf {p} _{0}$ is also the residual provided by this initial step of the algorithm.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] As observed above, $\mathbf {r} _{k}$ is the negative gradient of f at $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ , so the gradient descent method would require to move in the direction **r***k*.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Here, however, we insist that the directions $\mathbf {p} _{k}$ must be conjugate to each other.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] A practical way to enforce this is by requiring that the next search direction be built out of the current residual and all previous search directions.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugation constraint is an orthonormal-type constraint and hence the algorithm can be viewed as an example of Gram-Schmidt orthonormalization.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] (see the picture at the top of the article for the effect of the conjugacy constraint on convergence).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] where the last equality follows from the definition of $\mathbf {r} _{k}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The above algorithm gives the most straightforward explanation of the conjugate gradient method.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Seemingly, the algorithm as stated requires storage of all previous searching directions and residue vectors, as well as many matrix–vector multiplications, and thus can be computationally expensive.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] However, a closer analysis of the algorithm shows that $\mathbf {r} _{i}$ is orthogonal to $\mathbf {r} _{j}$ , i.e. $\mathbf {r} _{i}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {r} _{j}=0$ , for $i\neq j$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Therefore, $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ can be regarded as the projection of $\mathbf {x}$ on the Krylov subspace.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The algorithm is detailed below for solving $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ where $\mathbf {A}$ is a real, symmetric, positive-definite matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The input vector $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ can be an approximate initial solution or $\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] It is a different formulation of the exact procedure described above.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This is the most commonly used algorithm.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The same formula for $\beta _{k}$ is also used in the Fletcher–Reeves nonlinear conjugate gradient method.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] We note that $\mathbf {x} _{1}$ is computed by the gradient descent method applied to $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Setting $\beta _{k}=0$ would similarly make $\mathbf {x} _{k+1}$ computed by the gradient descent method from $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ , i.e., can be used as a simple implementation of a restart of the conjugate gradient iterations.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Restarts could slow down convergence, but may improve stability if the conjugate gradient method misbehaves, e.g., due to round-off error.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The former is used in the algorithm to avoid an extra multiplication by $\mathbf {A}$ since the vector $\mathbf {Ap} _{k}$ is already computed to evaluate $\alpha _{k}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The latter may be more accurate, substituting the explicit calculation $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}:=\mathbf {b} -\mathbf {Ax} _{k+1}$ for the implicit one by the recursion subject to round-off error accumulation, and is thus recommended for an occasional evaluation.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] A norm of the residual is typically used for stopping criteria.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The norm of the explicit residual $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}:=\mathbf {b} -\mathbf {Ax} _{k+1}$ provides a guaranteed level of accuracy both in exact arithmetic and in the presence of the rounding errors, where convergence naturally stagnates.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In contrast, the implicit residual $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}:=\mathbf {r} _{k}-\alpha _{k}\mathbf {Ap} _{k}$ is known to keep getting smaller in amplitude well below the level of rounding errors and thus cannot be used to determine the stagnation of convergence.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In the algorithm, $\alpha _{k}$ is chosen such that $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}$ is orthogonal to $\mathbf {r} _{k}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The $\beta _{k}$ is chosen such that $\mathbf {p} _{k+1}$ is conjugate to $\mathbf {p} _{k}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] because $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}$ and $\mathbf {r} _{k}$ are orthogonal by design.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] using that the search directions $\mathbf {p} _{k}$ are conjugated and again that the residuals are orthogonal.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This gives the $\beta$ in the algorithm after cancelling $\alpha _{k}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] in order to find an approximate solution to the system.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Our first step is to calculate the residual vector **r**0 associated with **x**0.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Since this is the first iteration, we will use the residual vector **r**0 as our initial search direction **p**0; the method of selecting **p***k* will change in further iterations.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This result completes the first iteration, the result being an "improved" approximate solution to the system, **x**1.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Our next step in the process is to compute the scalar *β*0 that will eventually be used to determine the next search direction **p**1.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] We now compute the scalar *α*1 using our newly acquired **p**1 using the same method as that used for *α*0.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Finally, we find **x**2 using the same method as that used to find **x**1.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The result, **x**2, is a "better" approximation to the system's solution than **x**1 and **x**0.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] If exact arithmetic were to be used in this example instead of limited-precision, then the exact solution would theoretically have been reached after *n* = 2 iterations (*n* being the order of the system).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Under exact arithmetic, the number of iterations required is no more than the order of the matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This behavior is known as the **finite termination property** of the conjugate gradient method.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] It refers to the method's ability to reach the exact solution of a linear system in a finite number of steps—at most equal to the dimension of the system—when exact arithmetic is used.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This property arises from the fact that, at each iteration, the method generates a residual vector that is orthogonal to all previous residuals.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] These residuals form a mutually orthogonal set.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In an *n*-dimensional space, it is impossible to construct more than *n* linearly independent and mutually orthogonal vectors unless one of them is the zero vector.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Therefore, once a zero residual appears, the method has reached the solution and must terminate.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This ensures that the conjugate gradient method converges in at most *n* steps.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] We start from an initial guess $\mathbf {x} _{0}={\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Since A is symmetric positive-definite and the system is 2-dimensional, the conjugate gradient method should find the exact solution in no more than 2 steps.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The output confirms that the method reaches ${\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\end{bmatrix}}$ after two iterations, consistent with the theoretical prediction.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This example illustrates how the conjugate gradient method behaves as a direct method under idealized conditions.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The finite termination property also has practical implications in solving large sparse systems, which frequently arise in scientific and engineering applications.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] For instance, discretizing the two-dimensional Laplace equation $\nabla ^{2}u=0$ using finite differences on a uniform grid leads to a sparse linear system $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ , where A is symmetric and positive definite.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Using a $5\times 5$ interior grid yields a $25\times 25$ system, and the coefficient matrix A has a five-point stencil pattern.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Each row of A contains at most five nonzero entries corresponding to the central point and its immediate neighbors.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Although the system dimension is 25, the conjugate gradient method is theoretically guaranteed to terminate in at most 25 iterations under exact arithmetic.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In practice, convergence often occurs in far fewer steps due to the matrix's spectral properties.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This efficiency makes CGM particularly attractive for solving large-scale systems arising from partial differential equations, such as those found in heat conduction, fluid dynamics, and electrostatics.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can theoretically be viewed as a direct method, as in the absence of round-off error it produces the exact solution after a finite number of iterations, which is not larger than the size of the matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In practice, the exact solution is never obtained since the conjugate gradient method is unstable with respect to even small perturbations, e.g., most directions are not in practice conjugate, due to a degenerative nature of generating the Krylov subspaces.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] As an iterative method, the conjugate gradient method monotonically (in the energy norm) improves approximations $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ to the exact solution and may reach the required tolerance after a relatively small (compared to the problem size) number of iterations.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The improvement is typically linear and its speed is determined by the condition number $\kappa (A)$ of the system matrix A : the larger $\kappa (A)$ is, the slower the improvement.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] However, an interesting case appears when the eigenvalues are spaced logarithmically for a large symmetric matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] For example, let $A=QDQ^{T}$ where Q is a random orthogonal matrix and D is a diagonal matrix with eigenvalues ranging from $\lambda _{n}=1$ to $\lambda _{1}=10^{6}$ , spaced logarithmically.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Despite the finite termination property of CGM, where the exact solution should theoretically be reached in at most n steps, the method may exhibit stagnation in convergence.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In such a scenario, even after many more iterations—e.g., ten times the matrix size—the error may only decrease modestly (e.g., to $10^{-5}$ ).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Moreover, the iterative error may oscillate significantly, making it unreliable as a stopping condition.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This poor convergence is not explained by the condition number alone (e.g., $\kappa _{2}(A)=10^{6}$ ), but rather by the eigenvalue distribution itself.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] When the eigenvalues are more evenly spaced or randomly distributed, such convergence issues are typically absent, highlighting that CGM performance depends not only on $\kappa (A)$ but also on how the eigenvalues are distributed.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] If $\kappa (A)$ is large, preconditioning is commonly used to replace the original system $\mathbf {Ax} -\mathbf {b} =0$ with $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}(\mathbf {Ax} -\mathbf {b} )=0$ such that $\kappa (\mathbf {M} ^{-1}\mathbf {A} )$ is smaller than $\kappa (\mathbf {A} )$ , see below.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] where $\Pi _{k}$ is the set of polynomials of maximal degree k .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Let $\left(\mathbf {x} _{k}\right)_{k}$ be the iterative approximations of the exact solution $\mathbf {x} _{*}$ , and define the errors as $\mathbf {e} _{k}:=\mathbf {x} _{k}-\mathbf {x} _{*}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] where $\sigma (\mathbf {A} )$ denotes the spectrum, and $\kappa (\mathbf {A} )$ denotes the condition number.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This shows $k={\tfrac {1}{2}}{\sqrt {\kappa (\mathbf {A} )}}\log \left(\left\|\mathbf {e} _{0}\right\|_{\mathbf {A} }\varepsilon ^{-1}\right)$ iterations suffices to reduce the error to $2\varepsilon$ for any $\varepsilon >0$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This limit shows a faster convergence rate compared to the iterative methods of Jacobi or Gauss–Seidel which scale as $\approx 1-{\frac {2}{\kappa (\mathbf {A} )}}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] No round-off error is assumed in the convergence theorem, but the convergence bound is commonly valid in practice as theoretically explained by Anne Greenbaum.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] If initialized randomly, the first stage of iterations is often the fastest, as the error is eliminated within the Krylov subspace that initially reflects a smaller effective condition number.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The second stage of convergence is typically well defined by the theoretical convergence bound with ${\textstyle {\sqrt {\kappa (\mathbf {A} )}}}$ , but may be super-linear, depending on a distribution of the spectrum of the matrix A and the spectral distribution of the error.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In the last stage, the smallest attainable accuracy is reached and the convergence stalls or the method may even start diverging.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In typical scientific computing applications in double-precision floating-point format for matrices of large sizes, the conjugate gradient method uses a stopping criterion with a tolerance that terminates the iterations during the first or second stage.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In most cases, preconditioning is necessary to ensure fast convergence of the conjugate gradient method.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] If $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}$ is symmetric positive-definite and $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}\mathbf {A}$ has a better condition number than $\mathbf {A} ,$ a preconditioned conjugate gradient method can be used.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The Cholesky decomposition of the preconditioner must be used to keep the symmetry (and positive definiteness) of the system.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] However, this decomposition does not need to be computed, and it is sufficient to know $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The preconditioner matrix $\mathbf {M}$ has to be symmetric positive-definite and fixed, i.e., cannot change from iteration to iteration.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] If any of these assumptions on the preconditioner is violated, the behavior of the preconditioned conjugate gradient method may become unpredictable.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] An example of a commonly used preconditioner is the incomplete Cholesky factorization.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] It is important to keep in mind that we don't want to invert the matrix $\mathbf {M}$ explicitly in order to get $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}$ for use in the process, since inverting $\mathbf {M}$ would take more time/computational resources than solving the conjugate gradient algorithm itself.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] As an example, let's say that we are using a preconditioner coming from incomplete Cholesky factorization.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Since $\mathbf {r}$ and $\mathbf {L}$ and known, and $\mathbf {L}$ is lower triangular, solving for $\mathbf {a}$ is easy and computationally cheap by using forward substitution.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Since $\mathbf {a}$ and $\mathbf {L} ^{\mathsf {T}}$ are known, and $\mathbf {L} ^{\mathsf {T}}$ is upper triangular, solving for $\mathbf {z}$ is easy and computationally cheap by using backward substitution.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Using this method, there is no need to invert $\mathbf {M}$ or $\mathbf {L}$ explicitly at all, and we still obtain $\mathbf {z}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In numerically challenging applications, sophisticated preconditioners are used, which may lead to variable preconditioning, changing between iterations.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Even if the preconditioner is symmetric positive-definite on every iteration, the fact that it may change makes the arguments above invalid, and in practical tests leads to a significant slow down of the convergence of the algorithm presented above.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] may dramatically improve the convergence in this case.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] This version of the preconditioned conjugate gradient method can be called **flexible**, as it allows for variable preconditioning.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The flexible version is also shown to be robust even if the preconditioner is not symmetric positive definite (SPD).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The implementation of the flexible version requires storing an extra vector.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] For a fixed SPD preconditioner, $\mathbf {r} _{k+1}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {z} _{k}=0,$ so both formulas for βk are equivalent in exact arithmetic, i.e., without the round-off error.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The mathematical explanation of the better convergence behavior of the method with the Polak–Ribière formula is that the method is **locally optimal** in this case, in particular, it does not converge slower than the locally optimal steepest descent method.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In both the original and the preconditioned conjugate gradient methods one only needs to set $\beta _{k}:=0$ in order to make them locally optimal, using the line search, steepest descent methods.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] With this substitution, vectors **p** are always the same as vectors **z**, so there is no need to store vectors **p**.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Thus, every iteration of these steepest descent methods is a bit cheaper compared to that for the conjugate gradient methods.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] However, the latter converge faster, unless a (highly) variable and/or non-SPD preconditioner is used, see above.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can also be derived using optimal control theory.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] In this approach, the conjugate gradient method falls out as an optimal feedback controller, $u=k(x,v):=-\gamma _{a}\nabla f(x)-\gamma _{b}v$ for the double integrator system, ${\dot {x}}=v,\quad {\dot {v}}=u$ The quantities $\gamma _{a}$ and $\gamma _{b}$ are variable feedback gains.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The conjugate gradient method can be applied to an arbitrary *n*-by-*m* matrix by applying it to normal equations **A**T**A** and right-hand side vector **A**T**b**, since **A**T**A** is a symmetric positive-semidefinite matrix for any **A**.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The result is **conjugate gradient on the normal equations** (**CGN** or **CGNR**).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] As an iterative method, it is not necessary to form **A**T**A** explicitly in memory but only to perform the matrix–vector and transpose matrix–vector multiplications.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Therefore, CGNR is particularly useful when *A* is a sparse matrix since these operations are usually extremely efficient.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] However the downside of forming the normal equations is that the condition number κ(**A**T**A**) is equal to κ2(**A**) and so the rate of convergence of CGNR may be slow and the quality of the approximate solution may be sensitive to roundoff errors.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Finding a good preconditioner is often an important part of using the CGNR method.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Several algorithms have been proposed (e.g., CGLS, LSQR).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The LSQR algorithm purportedly has the best numerical stability when **A** is ill-conditioned, i.e., **A** has a large condition number.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The trivial modification is simply substituting the conjugate transpose for the real transpose everywhere.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] The advantages and disadvantages of the conjugate gradient methods are summarized in the lecture notes by Nemirovsky and BenTal.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/conjugate-gradient-method] Solving it by conjugate gradient descent gives us rather bad convergence: $\|b-Wx_{k}\|^{2}=(1/t)^{k},\quad \|b-Wx_{n}\|^{2}=0$ In words, during the CG process, the error grows exponentially, until it suddenly becomes zero as the unique solution is found.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] In mathematics, the **generalized minimal residual method (GMRES)** is an iterative method for the numerical solution of an indefinite nonsymmetric system of linear equations.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The method approximates the solution by the vector in a Krylov subspace with minimal residual.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The Arnoldi iteration is used to find this vector.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The GMRES method was developed by Yousef Saad and Martin H.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] It is a generalization and improvement of the MINRES method due to Paige and Saunders in 1975.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The MINRES method requires the matrix to be symmetric, but has the advantage that it only requires handling of three vectors.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] GMRES is a special case of the DIIS method developed by Peter Pulay in 1980.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] DIIS is applicable to non-linear systems.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Denote the Euclidean norm of any vector **v**by $\|v\|$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Denote the (square) system of linear equations to be solved by $Ax=b.$ The matrix *A* is assumed to be invertible of size *m*-by-*m*.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Furthermore, it is assumed that **b** is normalized, i.e., that $\|b\|=1$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] GMRES approximates the exact solution of $Ax=b$ by the vector $x_{n}\in x_{0}+K_{n}$ that minimizes the Euclidean norm of the residual $r_{n}=b-Ax_{n}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The vectors $r_{0},Ar_{0},\ldots A^{n-1}r_{0}$ might be close to linearly dependent, so instead of this basis, the Arnoldi iteration is used to find orthonormal vectors $q_{1},q_{2},\ldots ,q_{n}\,$ which form a basis for $K_{n}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] In other words, finding the *n*-th approximation of the solution (i.e., $x_{n}$ ) is reduced to finding the vector $y_{n}$ , which is determined via minimizing the residue as described below.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The Arnoldi process also constructs ${\tilde {H}}_{n}$ , an ( $n+1$ )-by- n upper Hessenberg matrix which satisfies $AQ_{n}=Q_{n+1}{\tilde {H}}_{n}\,$ an equality which is used to simplify the calculation of $y_{n}$ (see § Solving the least squares problem).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Note that, for symmetric matrices, a symmetric tri-diagonal matrix is actually achieved, resulting in the MINRES method.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Hence, $x_{n}$ can be found by minimizing the Euclidean norm of the residual $r_{n}={\tilde {H}}_{n}y_{n}-\beta e_{1}.$ This is a linear least squares problem of size *n*.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] 4. repeat if the residual is not yet small enough.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] At every iteration, a matrix-vector product $Aq_{n}$ must be computed.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] This costs about $2m^{2}$ floating-point operations for general dense matrices of size m , but the cost can decrease to $O(m)$ for sparse matrices.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] In addition to the matrix-vector product, $O(nm)$ floating-point operations must be computed at the *n* -th iteration.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The *n*th iterate minimizes the residual in the Krylov subspace $K_{n}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Since every subspace is contained in the next subspace, the residual does not increase.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] After *m* iterations, where *m* is the size of the matrix *A*, the Krylov space *K**m* is the whole of **R***m* and hence the GMRES method arrives at the exact solution.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] However, the idea is that after a small number of iterations (relative to *m*), the vector *x**n* is already a good approximation to the exact solution.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Indeed, a theorem of Greenbaum, Pták and Strakoš states that for every nonincreasing sequence *a*1, ..., *a**m*−1, *a**m* = 0, one can find a matrix *A* such that the ‖*r**n*‖ = *a**n* for all *n*, where *r**n* is the residual defined above.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] In particular, it is possible to find a matrix for which the residual stays constant for *m* − 1 iterations, and only drops to zero at the last iteration.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] In practice, though, GMRES often performs well.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] This can be proven in specific situations.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Roughly speaking, this says that fast convergence occurs when the eigenvalues of *A* are clustered away from the origin and *A* is not too far from normality.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] All these inequalities bound only the residuals instead of the actual error, that is, the distance between the current iterate *x**n* and the exact solution.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Like other iterative methods, GMRES is usually combined with a preconditioning method in order to speed up convergence.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The cost of the iterations grow as O(*n*2), where *n* is the iteration number.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Therefore, the method is sometimes restarted after a number, say *k*, of iterations, with *x**k* as initial guess.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The resulting method is called GMRES(*k*) or Restarted GMRES.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] For non-positive definite matrices, this method may suffer from stagnation in convergence as the restarted subspace is often close to the earlier subspace.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The shortcomings of GMRES and restarted GMRES are addressed by the recycling of Krylov subspace in the GCRO type methods such as GCROT and GCRODR.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Recycling of Krylov subspaces in GMRES can also speed up convergence when sequences of linear systems need to be solved.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The Arnoldi iteration reduces to the Lanczos iteration for symmetric matrices.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The corresponding Krylov subspace method is the minimal residual method (MinRes) of Paige and Saunders.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Unlike the unsymmetric case, the MinRes method is given by a three-term recurrence relation.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] It can be shown that there is no Krylov subspace method for general matrices, which is given by a short recurrence relation and yet minimizes the norms of the residuals, as GMRES does.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Another class of methods builds on the unsymmetric Lanczos iteration, in particular the BiCG method.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] These use a three-term recurrence relation, but they do not attain the minimum residual, and hence the residual does not decrease monotonically for these methods.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The third class is formed by methods like CGS and BiCGSTAB.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] These also work with a three-term recurrence relation (hence, without optimality) and they can even terminate prematurely without achieving convergence.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The idea behind these methods is to choose the generating polynomials of the iteration sequence suitably.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] None of these three classes is the best for all matrices; there are always examples in which one class outperforms the other.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Therefore, multiple solvers are tried in practice to see which one is the best for a given problem.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] One part of the GMRES method is to find the vector $y_{n}$ which minimizes $\left\|{\tilde {H}}_{n}y_{n}-\beta e_{1}\right\|.$ Note that ${\tilde {H}}_{n}$ is an (*n* + 1)-by-*n* matrix, hence it gives an over-constrained linear system of *n*+1 equations for *n* unknowns.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Hence, it can be decomposed as ${\tilde {R}}_{n}={\begin{bmatrix}R_{n}\\0\end{bmatrix}},$ where $R_{n}$ is an *n*-by-*n* (thus square) triangular matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] In computational mathematics, an **iterative method** is a mathematical procedure that uses an initial value to generate a sequence of improving approximate solutions for a class of problems, in which the *i*-th approximation (called an "iterate") is derived from the previous ones.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] A specific implementation with termination criteria for a given iterative method like gradient descent, hill climbing, Newton's method, or quasi-Newton methods like BFGS, is an algorithm of an iterative method or a **method of successive approximation**.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] An iterative method is called *convergent* if the corresponding sequence converges for given initial approximations.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] A mathematically rigorous convergence analysis of an iterative method is usually performed; however, heuristic-based iterative methods are also common.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] In contrast, **direct methods** attempt to solve the problem by a finite sequence of operations.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] In the absence of rounding errors, direct methods would deliver an exact solution (for example, solving a linear system of equations $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ by Gaussian elimination).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] Iterative methods are often the only choice for nonlinear equations.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] However, iterative methods are often useful even for linear problems involving many variables (sometimes on the order of millions), where direct methods would be prohibitively expensive (and in some cases impossible) even with the best available computing power.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] Here *x**n* is the *n*th approximation or iteration of *x* and *x**n*+1 is the next or *n* + 1 iteration of *x*.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] Alternately, superscripts in parentheses are often used in numerical methods, so as not to interfere with subscripts with other meanings.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] (For example, *x*(*n*+1) = *f*(*x*(*n*)).) If the function *f* is continuously differentiable, a sufficient condition for convergence is that the spectral radius of the derivative is strictly bounded by one in a neighborhood of the fixed point.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] If this condition holds at the fixed point, then a sufficiently small neighborhood (basin of attraction) must exist.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] In the case of a system of linear equations, the two main classes of iterative methods are the **stationary iterative methods**, and the more general Krylov subspace methods.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] Stationary iterative methods solve a linear system with an operator approximating the original one; and based on a measurement of the error in the result (the residual), form a "correction equation" for which this process is repeated.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] While these methods are simple to derive, implement, and analyze, convergence is only guaranteed for a limited class of matrices.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] The basic iterative methods work by splitting the matrix A into $A=M-N$ and here the matrix M should be easily invertible.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] Basic examples of stationary iterative methods use a splitting of the matrix A such as $A=D+L+U\,,\quad D:=\operatorname {diag} ((a_{ii})_{i})$ where D is only the diagonal part of A , and L is the strict lower triangular part of A .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] Respectively, U is the strict upper triangular part of A .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] Linear stationary iterative methods are also called relaxation methods.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] Krylov subspace methods work by forming a basis of the sequence of successive matrix powers times the initial residual (the **Krylov sequence**).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] The approximations to the solution are then formed by minimizing the residual over the subspace formed.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] The prototypical method in this class is the conjugate gradient method (CG) which assumes that the system matrix A is symmetric positive-definite.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] For symmetric (and possibly indefinite) A one works with the minimal residual method (MINRES).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] In the case of non-symmetric matrices, methods such as the generalized minimal residual method (GMRES) and the biconjugate gradient method (BiCG) have been derived.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] Since these methods form a basis, it is evident that the method converges in *N* iterations, where *N* is the system size.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] However, in the presence of rounding errors this statement does not hold; moreover, in practice *N* can be very large, and the iterative process reaches sufficient accuracy already far earlier.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] The analysis of these methods is hard, depending on a complicated function of the spectrum of the operator.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] The construction of preconditioners is a large research area.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] Jamshīd al-Kāshī used iterative methods to calculate the sine of 1° and π in *The Treatise of Chord and Sine* to high precision.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] An early iterative method for solving a linear system appeared in a letter of Gauss to a student of his.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] He proposed solving a 4-by-4 system of equations by repeatedly solving the component in which the residual was the largest .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] The theory of stationary iterative methods was solidly established with the work of D.M.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] The conjugate gradient method was also invented in the 1950s, with independent developments by Cornelius Lanczos, Magnus Hestenes and Eduard Stiefel, but its nature and applicability were misunderstood at the time.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/iterative-method] Only in the 1970s was it realized that conjugacy based methods work very well for partial differential equations, especially the elliptic type.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] In mathematics, **preconditioning** is the application of a transformation, called the **preconditioner**, that conditions a given problem into a form that is more suitable for numerical solving methods.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Preconditioning is typically related to reducing a condition number of the problem.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] The preconditioned problem is then usually solved by an iterative method.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] In linear algebra and numerical analysis, a **preconditioner** P of a matrix A is a matrix such that $P^{-1}A$ has a smaller condition number than A .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] It is also common to call $T=P^{-1}$ the preconditioner, rather than P , since P itself is rarely explicitly available.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] In modern preconditioning, the application of $T=P^{-1}$ , i.e., multiplication of a column vector, or a block of column vectors, by $T=P^{-1}$ , is commonly performed in a matrix-free fashion, i.e., where neither P , nor $T=P^{-1}$ (and often not even A ) are explicitly available in a matrix form.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Preconditioners are useful in iterative methods to solve a linear system $Ax=b$ for x since the rate of convergence for most iterative linear solvers increases because the condition number of a matrix decreases as a result of preconditioning.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Preconditioned iterative solvers typically outperform direct solvers, e.g., Gaussian elimination, for large, especially for sparse, matrices.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Iterative solvers can be used as matrix-free methods, i.e. become the only choice if the coefficient matrix A is not stored explicitly, but is accessed by evaluating matrix-vector products.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Instead of solving the original linear system $Ax=b$ for x , one may consider the **right** preconditioned system $AP^{-1}(Px)=b$ and solve $AP^{-1}y=b$ for y and $Px=y$ for x .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Both systems give the same solution as the original system as long as the preconditioner matrix P is nonsingular.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] The left preconditioning is more traditional.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] The **two-sided** preconditioned system $QAP^{-1}(Px)=Qb$ may be beneficial, e.g., to preserve the matrix symmetry: if the original matrix A is real symmetric and real preconditioners Q and P satisfy $Q^{T}=P^{-1}$ then the preconditioned matrix $QAP^{-1}$ is also symmetric.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] The two-sided preconditioning is common for **diagonal scaling** where the preconditioners Q and P are diagonal and scaling is applied both to columns and rows of the original matrix A , e.g., in order to decrease the dynamic range of entries of the matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] The goal of preconditioning is reducing the condition number, e.g., of the left or right preconditioned system matrix $P^{-1}A$ or $AP^{-1}$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Small condition numbers benefit fast convergence of iterative solvers and improve stability of the solution with respect to perturbations in the system matrix and the right-hand side, e.g., allowing for more aggressive quantization of the matrix entries using lower computer precision.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] The preconditioned matrix $P^{-1}A$ or $AP^{-1}$ is rarely explicitly formed.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Only the action of applying the preconditioner solve operation $P^{-1}$ to a given vector may need to be computed.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Typically there is a trade-off in the choice of P .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Since the operator $P^{-1}$ must be applied at each step of the iterative linear solver, it should have a small cost (computing time) of applying the $P^{-1}$ operation.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] The cheapest preconditioner would therefore be $P=I$ since then $P^{-1}=I.$ Clearly, this results in the original linear system and the preconditioner does nothing.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] At the other extreme, the choice $P=A$ gives $P^{-1}A=AP^{-1}=I,$ which has optimal condition number of 1, requiring a single iteration for convergence; however in this case $P^{-1}=A^{-1},$ and applying the preconditioner is as difficult as solving the original system.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] One therefore chooses P as somewhere between these two extremes, in an attempt to achieve a minimal number of linear iterations while keeping the operator $P^{-1}$ as simple as possible.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Some examples of typical preconditioning approaches are detailed below.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Examples of popular preconditioned iterative methods for linear systems include the preconditioned conjugate gradient method, the biconjugate gradient method, and generalized minimal residual method.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] A stationary iterative method is determined by the matrix splitting $A=M-N$ and the iteration matrix $C=I-M^{-1}A$ .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] For a symmetric positive definite matrix A the preconditioner P is typically chosen to be symmetric positive definite as well.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] The preconditioned operator $P^{-1}A$ is then also symmetric positive definite, but with respect to the P -based scalar product.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] In this case, the desired effect in applying a preconditioner is to make the quadratic form of the preconditioned operator $P^{-1}A$ with respect to the P -based scalar product to be nearly spherical.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Denoting $T=P^{-1}$ , we highlight that preconditioning is practically implemented as multiplying some vector r by T , i.e., computing the product $Tr.$ In many applications, T is not given as a matrix, but rather as an operator $T(r)$ acting on the vector r .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Some popular preconditioners, however, change with r and the dependence on r may not be linear.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Typical examples involve using non-linear iterative methods, e.g., the conjugate gradient method, as a part of the preconditioner construction.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Such preconditioners may be practically very efficient, however, their behavior is hard to predict theoretically.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] One interesting particular case of variable preconditioning is random preconditioning, e.g., multigrid preconditioning on random coarse grids.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] If used in gradient descent methods, random preconditioning can be viewed as an implementation of stochastic gradient descent and can lead to faster convergence, compared to fixed preconditioning, since it breaks the asymptotic "zig-zag" pattern of the gradient descent.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] The most common use of preconditioning is for iterative solution of linear systems resulting from approximations of partial differential equations.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] The better the approximation quality, the larger the matrix size is.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] In such a case, the goal of optimal preconditioning is, on the one side, to make the spectral condition number of $P^{-1}A$ to be bounded from above by a constant independent of the matrix size, which is called *spectrally equivalent* preconditioning by D'yakonov.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] On the other hand, the cost of application of the $P^{-1}$ should ideally be proportional (also independent of the matrix size) to the cost of multiplication of A by a vector.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] The **Sparse Approximate Inverse** preconditioner minimises $\|AT-I\|_{F},$ where $\|\cdot \|_{F}$ is the Frobenius norm and $T=P^{-1}$ is from some suitably constrained set of sparse matrices.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Under the Frobenius norm, this reduces to solving numerous independent least-squares problems (one for every column).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] The entries in T must be restricted to some sparsity pattern or the problem remains as difficult and time-consuming as finding the exact inverse of A .
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/preconditioner] Huckle together with an approach to selecting sparsity patterns.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/skyline-matrix] In scientific computing, **skyline matrix storage**, or SKS, or a **variable band matrix storage**, or **envelope storage scheme** is a form of a sparse matrix storage format matrix that reduces the storage requirement of a matrix more than banded storage.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/skyline-matrix] In banded storage, all entries within a fixed distance from the diagonal (called half-bandwidth) are stored.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/skyline-matrix] In column-oriented skyline storage, only the entries from the first nonzero entry to the last nonzero entry in each column are stored.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/skyline-matrix] There is also row oriented skyline storage, and, for symmetric matrices, only one triangle is usually stored.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/skyline-matrix] In addition, the effort of coding skyline Cholesky is about same as for Cholesky for banded matrices (available for banded matrices, e.g. in LAPACK; for a prototype skyline code, see ).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/skyline-matrix] Before storing a matrix in skyline format, the rows and columns are typically renumbered to reduce the size of the skyline (the number of nonzero entries stored) and to decrease the number of operations in the skyline Cholesky algorithm.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/skyline-matrix] The same heuristic renumbering algorithm that reduce the bandwidth are also used to reduce the skyline.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/skyline-matrix] The basic and one of the earliest algorithms to do that is reverse Cuthill–McKee algorithm.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] In numerical analysis and scientific computing, a **sparse matrix** or **sparse array** is a matrix in which most of the elements are zero.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] There is no strict definition regarding the proportion of zero-value elements for a matrix to qualify as **sparse** but a common criterion is that the number of non-zero elements is roughly equal to the number of rows or columns.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] By contrast, if most of the elements are non-zero, the matrix is considered **dense**.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The number of zero-valued elements divided by the total number of elements (e.g., *m* × *n* for an *m* × *n* matrix) is sometimes referred to as the **sparsity** of the matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Conceptually, sparsity corresponds to systems with few pairwise interactions.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] For example, consider a line of balls connected by springs from one to the next: this is a sparse system, as only adjacent balls are coupled.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] By contrast, if the same line of balls were to have springs connecting each ball to all other balls, the system would correspond to a dense matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The concept of sparsity is useful in combinatorics and application areas such as network theory and numerical analysis, which typically have a low density of significant data or connections.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Large sparse matrices often appear in scientific or engineering applications when solving partial differential equations.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] When storing and manipulating sparse matrices on a computer, it is beneficial and often necessary to use specialized algorithms and data structures that take advantage of the sparse structure of the matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Specialized computers have been made for sparse matrices, as they are common in the machine learning field.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Operations using standard dense-matrix structures and algorithms are slow and inefficient when applied to large sparse matrices as processing and memory are wasted on the zeros.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Sparse data is by nature more easily compressed and thus requires significantly less storage.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Some very large sparse matrices are infeasible to manipulate using standard dense-matrix algorithms.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The band matrices form a special class of sparse matrix where the non-zero elements are concentrated near the main diagonal.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] A band matrix is characterised by its lower and upper bandwidths, which refer to the number of diagonals below and above (respectively) the main diagonal between which all of the non-zero entries are contained.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Formally, the lower bandwidth of a matrix **A** is the smallest number *p* such that the entry *a**i*,*j* vanishes whenever *i* > *j* + *p*.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Similarly, the upper bandwidth is the smallest number *p* such that *a**i*,*j* = 0 whenever *i* < *j* − *p* (Golub & Van Loan 1996, §1.2.1).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] For example, a tridiagonal matrix has lower bandwidth 1 and upper bandwidth 1.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] As another example, the following sparse matrix has lower and upper bandwidth both equal to 3.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Matrices with reasonably small upper and lower bandwidth are known as band matrices and often lend themselves to simpler algorithms than general sparse matrices; or one can sometimes apply dense matrix algorithms and gain efficiency simply by looping over a reduced number of indices.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] By rearranging the rows and columns of a matrix **A** it may be possible to obtain a matrix **A**′ with a lower bandwidth.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] A number of algorithms are designed for bandwidth minimization.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] A diagonal matrix is the extreme case of a band matrix, with zero upper and lower bandwidth.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] A diagonal matrix can be stored efficiently by storing just the entries in the main diagonal as a one-dimensional array, so a diagonal *n* × *n* matrix requires only *n* entries in memory.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] A symmetric sparse matrix arises as the adjacency matrix of an undirected graph; it can be stored efficiently as an adjacency list.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] A block-diagonal matrix consists of sub-matrices along its diagonal blocks.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The *fill-in* of a matrix are those entries that change from an initial zero to a non-zero value during the execution of an algorithm.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] To reduce the memory requirements and the number of arithmetic operations used during an algorithm, it is useful to minimize the fill-in by switching rows and columns in the matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The symbolic Cholesky decomposition can be used to calculate the worst possible fill-in before doing the actual Cholesky decomposition.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] There are other methods than the Cholesky decomposition in use.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Orthogonalization methods (such as QR factorization) are common, for example, when solving problems by least squares methods.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] While the theoretical fill-in is still the same, in practical terms the "false non-zeros" can be different for different methods.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] And symbolic versions of those algorithms can be used in the same manner as the symbolic Cholesky to compute worst case fill-in.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Both iterative and direct methods exist for sparse matrix solving.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Iterative methods, such as conjugate gradient method and GMRES utilize fast computations of matrix-vector products $Ax_{i}$ , where matrix A is sparse.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The use of preconditioners can significantly accelerate convergence of such iterative methods.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] A matrix is typically stored as a two-dimensional array.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Each entry in the array represents an element *a**i*,*j* of the matrix and is accessed by the two indices *i* and *j*.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Conventionally, *i* is the row index, numbered from top to bottom, and *j* is the column index, numbered from left to right.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] For an *m* × *n* matrix, the amount of memory required to store the matrix in this format is proportional to *m* × *n* (disregarding the fact that the dimensions of the matrix also need to be stored).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] In the case of a sparse matrix, substantial memory requirement reductions can be realized by storing only the non-zero entries.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Depending on the number and distribution of the non-zero entries, different data structures can be used and yield huge savings in memory when compared to the basic approach.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The trade-off is that accessing the individual elements becomes more complex and additional structures are needed to be able to recover the original matrix unambiguously.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] DOK consists of a dictionary that maps (row, column)-pairs to the value of the elements.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Elements that are missing from the dictionary are taken to be zero.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The format is good for incrementally constructing a sparse matrix in random order, but poor for iterating over non-zero values in lexicographical order.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] One typically constructs a matrix in this format and then converts to another more efficient format for processing.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] LIL stores one list per row, with each entry containing the column index and the value.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Typically, these entries are kept sorted by column index for faster lookup.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] This is another format good for incremental matrix construction.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] COO stores a list of (row, column, value) tuples.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Ideally, the entries are sorted first by row index and then by column index, to improve random access times.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] This is another format that is good for incremental matrix construction.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The *compressed sparse row* (CSR) or *compressed row storage* (CRS) or Yale format represents a matrix **M** by three (one-dimensional) arrays, that respectively contain nonzero values, the extents of rows, and column indices.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] It is similar to COO, but compresses the row indices, hence the name.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] This format allows fast row access and matrix-vector multiplications (**M***x*).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The CSR format has been in use since at least the mid-1960s, with the first complete description appearing in 1967.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The CSR format stores a sparse *m* × *n* matrix **M** in row form using three (one-dimensional) arrays (V, COL_INDEX, ROW_INDEX).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Let NNZ denote the number of nonzero entries in **M**.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Then we take slices from V and COL_INDEX starting at row_start and ending at row_end.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] To extract the row 1 (the second row) of this matrix we set `row_start=1` and `row_end=2`.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] We now know that in row 1 we have one element at column 1 with value 8.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] In this case the CSR representation contains 13 entries, compared to 16 in the original matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The CSR format saves on memory only when NNZ < (*m* (*n* − 1) − 1) / 2.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The whole is stored as 21 entries: 8 in V, 8 in COL_INDEX, and 5 in ROW_INDEX.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Note that in this format, the first value of ROW_INDEX is always zero and the last is always NNZ, so they are in some sense redundant (although in programming languages where the array length needs to be explicitly stored, NNZ would not be redundant).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Nonetheless, this does avoid the need to handle an exceptional case when computing the length of each row, as it guarantees the formula ROW_INDEX[*i* + 1] − ROW_INDEX[*i*] works for any row *i*.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Moreover, the memory cost of this redundant storage is likely insignificant for a sufficiently large matrix.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The (old and new) Yale sparse matrix formats are instances of the CSR scheme.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The old Yale format works exactly as described above, with three arrays; the new format combines ROW_INDEX and COL_INDEX into a single array and handles the diagonal of the matrix separately.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] For logical adjacency matrices, the data array can be omitted, as the existence of an entry in the row array is sufficient to model a binary adjacency relation.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] It is likely known as the Yale format because it was proposed in the 1977 Yale Sparse Matrix Package report from Department of Computer Science at Yale University.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] CSC is similar to CSR except that values are read first by column, a row index is stored for each value, and column pointers are stored.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] For example, CSC is (val, row_ind, col_ptr), where val is an array of the (top-to-bottom, then left-to-right) non-zero values of the matrix; row_ind is the row indices corresponding to the values; and, col_ptr is the list of val indexes where each column starts.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The name is based on the fact that column index information is compressed relative to the COO format.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] One typically uses another format (LIL, DOK, COO) for construction.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] This format is efficient for arithmetic operations, column slicing, and matrix-vector products.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] This is the traditional format for specifying a sparse matrix in MATLAB (via the `sparse` function).
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] Many software libraries support sparse matrices, and provide solvers for sparse matrix equations.
[src:sparse-linear-algebra/sparse-matrix] The term *sparse matrix* was possibly coined by Harry Markowitz who initiated some pioneering work but then left the field.
